HEADWORD: Theriaca
<hw>The*ri"a*ca</hw>
<pr>(?)</pr>, }</mhw> <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[L. <ets>theriaca</ets> an
antidote against the bite of serpents, Gr. <?/: cf. F.
<ets>th⟦eacute⟧riaque</ets>. See <er>Treacle</er>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn>
<fld>(Old Med.)</fld> <def>An ancient composition esteemed efficacious
against the effects of poison; especially, a certain compound of
sixty-four drugs, prepared, pulverized, and reduced by means of honey to
an electuary; -- called also <altname>theriaca Andromachi</altname>, and
<altname>Venice treacle</altname>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Treacle; molasses.</def> <rj><au>British
Pharm.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Theriacal</ent>⟦br⟧
<ent>Theriac</ent>⟦br⟧

